for-direction.description:
Description

This rule forbidsforloops where the counter variable changes in such a way that the stop condition will never be met. For example, if the counter variable is increasing (i.e.i++) and the stop condition tests that the counter is greater than zero (i >= 0) then the loop will never exit.

Examples ofincorrectcode for this rule:

/*eslint for-direction: "error"*/
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i--) {
}

for (let i = 10; i >= 0; i++) {
}

for (let i = 0; i > 10; i++) {
}

for (let i = 0; 10 > i; i--) {
}

const n = -2;
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i += n) {
}

Examples ofcorrectcode for this rule:

/*eslint for-direction: "error"*/
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
}

for (let i = 0; 10 > i; i++) { // with counter "i" on the right
}

for (let i = 10; i >= 0; i += this.step) { // direction unknown
}

for (let i = MIN; i <= MAX; i -= 0) { // not increasing or decreasing
}
